00:45:45.250 --> 00:45:50.920
So we offer three different classes
that give you access to the data that

00:45:50.970 --> 00:45:53.830
our Game Center servers have to offer.

00:45:53.870 --> 00:45:59.600
And so those are the GKE Leaderboard,
GKE Achievement Description,

00:45:59.600 --> 00:46:02.460
and the GKE Achievement.

00:46:02.520 --> 00:46:05.160
So this gives you all
the information you need.

00:46:05.190 --> 00:46:06.760
So be creative.

00:46:06.760 --> 00:46:11.170
Like, if you're going to spend the effort
to create an all-inclusive experience,

00:46:11.210 --> 00:46:13.700
make sure that it's purposeful.

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:16.460
Like, have something that
really makes the user go,

00:46:16.460 --> 00:46:19.800
yes, this is exactly what I want to know.

00:46:20.310 --> 00:46:26.910
So first, let's talk about what custom
leaderboards can offer you.

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:32.940
The leaderboard data that we include
can be queried programmatically.

00:46:32.990 --> 00:46:36.330
And so you don't actually just
need to create custom leaderboards.

00:46:36.500 --> 00:46:39.950
You can actually use some of this
information for other reasons.

00:46:39.960 --> 00:46:43.210
Like, let's say I'm about to
create a multiplayer game.

00:46:43.210 --> 00:46:47.870
I might want to see where all my players
that I'm playing against rank against

00:46:47.870 --> 00:46:50.180
me so that I can make my decisions.

00:46:50.180 --> 00:46:53.230
Maybe Jordan is the best
player out of all of us.

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:54.840
I want to ally with him.

00:46:54.880 --> 00:46:58.490
If we're playing an allied game,
I definitely want to be on his team.

00:47:02.040 --> 00:47:04.850
So a typical query
could be anything like,

00:47:04.850 --> 00:47:08.190
let's say, top 10 players.

00:47:08.700 --> 00:47:10.940
A couple of different ranks.

00:47:10.940 --> 00:47:13.510
You might want to get a
list of certain players,

00:47:13.510 --> 00:47:15.670
scores, stuff like that.

00:47:17.210 --> 00:47:20.390
And your queries are returned
to you asynchronously,

00:47:20.400 --> 00:47:25.220
as are most of the Game Center APIs.

00:47:25.220 --> 00:47:25.220
And so,

00:47:25.410 --> 00:47:31.610
We set a limit at 100 so that you
don't query the whole database.

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:36.020
But we also want you to kind of
be a good network citizen and make

00:47:36.020 --> 00:47:38.120
sure that you do low frequencies.

00:47:38.350 --> 00:47:42.580
Don't try to circumvent the
system by making multiple calls

00:47:42.580 --> 00:47:44.610
to load the whole database.

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:49.610
In most cases, you only need to show a
minimal amount of information.

00:47:51.560 --> 00:47:56.360
So what you'll need to do to load
this leaderboard information is

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:59.370
create a GKE Leaderboard object.

00:47:59.570 --> 00:48:02.700
Set the properties that
you are requesting and then

00:48:02.710 --> 00:48:05.140
submit it asynchronously.

00:48:05.150 --> 00:48:07.750
Let's take a look at what
this code looks like.

00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:13.800
First, we're going to want to create
the GKE leaderboard object.

00:48:13.870 --> 00:48:17.380
Then, we'll set the category for
which leaderboard we want.

00:48:17.540 --> 00:48:23.430
We also offer some method calls
so that you can get a list of

00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:24.890
all the categories possible.

00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:27.570
But in this instance,
we're going to only talk about

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:31.000
the fastest rock that we've
been talking about all night.

00:48:32.840 --> 00:48:36.930
For instance, in this instance,
we're going to want to look for all our

00:48:37.090 --> 00:48:40.400
players' top scores within the last week.

00:48:40.410 --> 00:48:43.300
And we're going to only
look for the top 25.

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:46.650
You'll notice here that
our range is from 1 to 25,

00:48:46.820 --> 00:48:51.040
and that's because our leaderboards
are done with a starting at 1.

00:48:51.150 --> 00:48:55.090
So make sure that you don't
submit looking for 0 because

00:48:55.370 --> 00:48:57.500
there is no 0th player.

00:48:59.420 --> 00:49:01.400
And so finally,
we're going to want to submit this.

00:49:01.400 --> 00:49:05.780
And so we submit using load
scores with Completion Handler.

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:09.120
And this will return
back an array of scores.

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:12.260
So once we've done that--

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:15.040
We'll check for errors and
send a completion block.

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:17.730
This completion block,
as similar with all of

00:49:17.730 --> 00:49:21.270
our asynchronous blocks,
we're going to want to make sure

00:49:21.270 --> 00:49:25.000
that we only check to see if
scores are submitted or sent back

00:49:25.100 --> 00:49:27.500
to us in the scores variable.

00:49:28.100 --> 00:49:31.740
If we don't get something from them,
then we can check for errors.

00:49:31.760 --> 00:49:36.000
The fact of the matter is even if
we are having a communication error,

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:39.960
if we have this information
within Game Center stored

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:44.390
from a previous instance,
we will send these back to you.

00:49:44.450 --> 00:49:49.430
So just check to make sure
that we've included the scores.

00:49:50.990 --> 00:49:56.590
Next, let's talk about how to get the
information for GKE achievements.

00:49:57.890 --> 00:50:00.600
So we can query this in two parts.

00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:04.320
First, we have the GKE Achievement.

00:50:04.540 --> 00:50:08.730
An instance of all the GKE achievements
that you've submitted by

00:50:08.770 --> 00:50:11.100
the time you make this call.

00:50:11.310 --> 00:50:15.140
So if you have not made any
progress on your achievements,

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:16.470
you won't get anything back.

00:50:16.470 --> 00:50:20.750
So that means that we're going to use
the GKE achievement description to get

00:50:20.760 --> 00:50:23.640
a list of all the achievements possible.

00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:27.070
So let's take a look at what
this will look like in code.

00:50:27.200 --> 00:50:29.190
It's actually really similar,
the two of them.

00:50:29.230 --> 00:50:34.140
So to query the achievements data,
we're going to want to first,

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:38.220
use the nothing called load
achievements with completion handler.

00:50:38.250 --> 00:50:43.390
This will return back an array of
all the achievements that you've

00:50:44.310 --> 00:50:47.080
already submitted at this point.

00:50:47.980 --> 00:50:51.070
And then, similarly enough,
you just want to check to make sure

00:50:51.070 --> 00:50:54.400
those achievements have been done.

00:50:54.400 --> 00:50:59.800
And if there is an error,
send a UI feedback.

00:51:01.420 --> 00:51:03.980
Similarly with
GKE Achievement Description,

00:51:03.980 --> 00:51:10.100
we're going to want to load Achievement
Description with Completion Handler.

00:51:10.130 --> 00:51:13.170
Then make sure that the
descriptions are there.

